WEBVTT

00:00.418 --> 00:08.570
Hi, my name is Jonathan Carswell from tenothers.com and I'm here with Alistair Beck, Bible teacher for Truth for Life and Pastor, thank you for joining us.

00:09.612 --> 00:18.765
Alistair, if anyone's been on the internet for the last few years, they've probably seen the clip of the man on the middle cross, that illustration that you told.

00:20.448 --> 00:25.916
Would you give us a little bit of a background of that because it's been seen by millions of people?

00:26.517 --> 00:27.338
Was it in your notes?

00:27.398 --> 00:28.520
Did you throw it in later?

00:28.720 --> 00:30.162
Did you think it was gonna be a

00:30.690 --> 00:33.033
No, no, no, not at all, obviously.

00:33.654 --> 00:43.646
In fact, just this past weekend, I was at a place and, you know, 50 or 80% of the people that came to say hello to me all said, the man on the middle cross.

00:44.026 --> 00:52.938
In fact, I had in a Q&A session, a number of people had written on the card, would you do the man on the middle cross like it's a performance piece, you know?

00:53.518 --> 00:59.826
No, actually, I was, if truth really be told, I found myself increasingly frustrated

00:59.906 --> 01:04.634
as I was trying to get across that essential truth.

01:04.894 --> 01:26.770
And no, I didn't have it in my notes, and I had thought it before, and I just reached for it in a sense out of desperation, never imagining that it would actually be the turning key for the other 35 minutes that I had tried to explain the Bible.

01:27.010 --> 01:50.578
on that event were people coming out to you afterwards and commenting or was the knowledge that you know I think you know I think that I was so bemused by the the the response particularly of the choir that was sitting behind me who didn't seem to be what you would call thoroughly enthusiastic that I think I can have scouped off away and so

01:50.690 --> 01:55.895
I didn't really have any sense immediately afterwards about that at all.

01:56.055 --> 01:57.337
Not at all, no.

01:57.997 --> 02:06.386
And we're going to talk in a moment about becoming a small evangelistic book, a book that could be given to those who don't yet know that they can come.

02:06.906 --> 02:12.532
But would you just explain a little bit of your thought process as you go into the pulpit?

02:13.352 --> 02:19.058
Something that I've noticed is you're bringing the gospel through all the time.

02:19.202 --> 02:23.686
Obviously, a lot of your audience will be trusting in Jesus.

02:24.827 --> 02:27.670
But you always seem to be aware that there are those that aren't.

02:27.810 --> 02:30.673
And without ever missing that, you use that opportunity.

02:31.273 --> 02:33.596
So you're going into the pulpit prepared to do that?

02:33.816 --> 02:36.418
Or is it just walk us through your thought process?

02:37.199 --> 02:43.665
Well, when I go into the pulpit, I'm of course trying to be, say what it says in the text.

02:44.646 --> 02:48.850
And so whatever the main thrust of it, hopefully I don't cloud the issue.

02:49.538 --> 02:50.820
I think there's two things.

02:51.061 --> 02:58.213
One, in the back of my mind all the time, I'm thinking about the person that doesn't believe or doesn't get it.

02:59.115 --> 03:09.293
And if I was talking to a group of teenage boys, the one that was looking out the window is the one that I would be trying to draw back into the room.

03:09.934 --> 03:14.322
And that is then what causes me to sometimes say,

03:14.434 --> 03:19.959
You know, you may be sitting here and just thinking, I don't understand a single word of what you've just said.

03:19.979 --> 03:22.522
That brings that person in.

03:23.102 --> 03:28.928
If you start from the other position of assuming that because you are now so clear, everybody gets it.

03:30.269 --> 03:44.242
But no, I think, I don't know what it is about me, but just to find out that the Bible is a book about Jesus and that we can know God in Jesus as the Bible has explained,

03:44.642 --> 04:02.199
It seems to me that there ought to be, I think it's actually Packer who says, you know, if you just teach the Bible, if you just expound the Scriptures, you will discover that you're being evangelistic, whether you try to do it or not, in the sense that you're setting forward Christ.

04:02.299 --> 04:07.885
And also saying to people, you know, you can come to know him.

04:07.905 --> 04:09.126
And by the way, he knows you.

04:09.326 --> 04:10.507
Yeah.

04:10.527 --> 04:13.330
So in the book, you retell three

04:13.506 --> 04:20.193
stories that are found in the gospels, so there's the woman at the well, the paralyzed man, and then the thief on the cross.

04:21.074 --> 04:26.880
Let's take the woman at the well, because that is an amazing story, a great encounter.

04:29.542 --> 04:31.044
Talk us through your thought processes.

04:31.084 --> 04:35.248
You've read that story, you've studied it, and how you then share it with others.

04:35.608 --> 04:38.351
Well, you know, one time I think I tried to do that.

04:38.692 --> 04:41.074
I shouldn't probably have done it, but I tried to do it.

04:41.506 --> 04:43.509
as the woman in the first person.

04:44.450 --> 04:48.375
So I said, you know, I come to the well in the middle of the day.

04:48.415 --> 04:55.004
I'm usually here by myself because of circumstances in my life I'm not really well thought of.

04:55.765 --> 04:58.389
And I went into it in that way.

05:00.412 --> 05:10.866
Because it is a fascinating encounter that she is bemused initially by the fight that the stranger speaks to her.

05:11.042 --> 05:25.900
And that as the conversation progresses, she moves from that you a man would speak to me to, I can see that you're a prophet, sent from God.

05:26.020 --> 05:27.983
So the ball is advancing up the field.

05:28.463 --> 05:40.658
And I think there's a way to teach that, that misses the nuances of that, that fails to really pay attention to the immediacy of what is taking place, that the idea

05:40.866 --> 05:45.991
of Jesus is purposefully engaging with this lady.

05:46.511 --> 05:48.413
In one sense, it's happenstance.

05:48.994 --> 05:49.975
They're at a well.

05:50.055 --> 05:56.461
She comes of her own free will, constrained by these other elements.

05:57.201 --> 06:04.328
And Jesus doesn't say to her initially, Anna the other, you know, then, can I have a drink of water?

06:04.528 --> 06:05.990
Yeah, drink of water.

06:06.210 --> 06:07.151
But that's enough for her.

06:07.771 --> 06:08.532
Why?

06:08.973 --> 06:09.333
You don't.

06:09.573 --> 06:10.514
Why?

06:10.818 --> 06:12.281
I would like to give you water.

06:12.321 --> 06:13.724
You'd never thirst again."

06:13.764 --> 06:17.532
She says, well, he's saying you're greater than our father, Jacob.

06:17.592 --> 06:21.781
He built this well, and furthermore, how'd you get it up out of there?

06:22.202 --> 06:22.482
Yeah.

06:23.064 --> 06:23.805
It's great.

06:23.845 --> 06:31.281
I mean, the irony in John's gospel is fantastic, and it's possible to teach it in a way that misses the irony that is there.

06:31.521 --> 06:31.922
Yeah.

06:32.994 --> 06:35.658
is an interesting sort of development as you say.

06:35.999 --> 06:44.752
She obviously has some background or knowledge, but she's also lived a life that means she has to come to the well at midday.

06:44.812 --> 06:51.884
There's also that moment where Jesus begins to probe a little bit in a subtle way, go get your husband.

06:52.945 --> 06:58.854
She's let her go down a little bit, but she's not dropped it all the way either.

07:00.337 --> 07:01.138
Why is it?

07:01.922 --> 07:10.472
when our lives are so messy, and everyone's lives are so messy, that we're so hesitant to admit and confess.

07:11.212 --> 07:21.384
Well, I think in her case, probably, because I've often wondered, you know, when you read the text, you can't tell the tone of voice.

07:21.484 --> 07:25.729
I mean, you don't know whether she said in a defined way, I have no husband.

07:25.989 --> 07:26.289
Yeah.

07:26.710 --> 07:30.514
Or whether she said, I don't have a husband.

07:30.658 --> 07:32.941
You know, I'm assuming the latter.

07:34.162 --> 07:44.315
So shame, shame, a sense of shame in context that draw it out that may never happen in another context.

07:44.395 --> 07:46.397
I mean, this is a stranger talking to her.

07:46.417 --> 07:48.840
Why does she have to answer questions like that?

07:50.162 --> 07:53.286
But it's not just a stranger that's talking to her.

07:53.306 --> 07:59.954
And the way in which it unfolds, and when I started out,

08:00.034 --> 08:02.556
try to understand that section in John.

08:03.457 --> 08:11.545
I was greatly influenced by the fellow who an American guy whose name I've just forgotten, but he did a book on evangelism.

08:11.625 --> 08:22.015
I can't remember what it was, but he says in there in personal evangelism, one of the ways, if you're going to be involved in personal work, you have to be able to deal with the interruptions.

08:23.036 --> 08:26.219
And this lady, what happens here is an interruption.

08:26.900 --> 08:29.362
The more I've studied that, I don't think it is an interruption.

08:29.762 --> 08:36.113
Because when he says to her, no, you've said right that you don't have a husband.

08:36.133 --> 08:39.338
You actually had a number of husbands and you're now living with a fellow.

08:40.120 --> 08:41.322
Again, tone of voice.

08:41.522 --> 08:43.025
I can't have been judgmental.

08:43.165 --> 08:43.586
No.

08:44.067 --> 08:46.831
But just the awareness of being uncovered.

08:47.232 --> 08:47.633
Yes.

08:47.653 --> 08:50.197
Then comes the interruption or maybe it doesn't.

08:50.818 --> 08:53.042
Then she says, you know,

08:53.410 --> 08:58.977
Do you think you're supposed to meet God in Gerasim or do you think we meet Him in Jerusalem?

08:59.237 --> 09:00.719
Why does she bring that into the thing?

09:01.300 --> 09:07.747
Because presumably she's saying, if there is any way that this is dealt with, I want to know where it's dealt with.

09:07.807 --> 09:08.448
So you're right.

09:08.508 --> 09:11.712
I think that there's something going on in the inside there.

09:12.113 --> 09:12.433
Yeah.

09:12.453 --> 09:21.264
Somebody once said to me, when you're in conversation, you've got to know the difference between a red herring and a real hindrance.

09:21.424 --> 09:23.186
And I think for her,

09:23.650 --> 09:25.132
It was a real hindrance.

09:25.152 --> 09:27.195
She wanted to genuinely know the answer.

09:27.215 --> 09:29.798
And I think you see that because of the response.

09:29.998 --> 09:30.399
Right.

09:30.419 --> 09:36.467
When he replies to her and you see the impact of, I've got to go tell my friends, I'm going to go get them.

09:36.487 --> 09:42.996
And so, yeah, interesting as we deal with that conversation, looking out for, what is this?

09:43.076 --> 09:44.177
Is this an issue for them?

09:44.197 --> 09:45.799
Or is it a distraction?

09:45.879 --> 09:50.866
I mean, the point was well made by that fellow that, just as you say,

09:51.170 --> 09:55.956
something you're talking along with like some says, yeah, well, what about Noah and the ark?

09:56.277 --> 09:58.780
You know, that is a red hair when you have this point.

09:58.800 --> 09:59.962
That's not what she's saying.

10:00.142 --> 10:05.469
No, she's, yeah, if there's something somewhere, I need to know where it is.

10:05.649 --> 10:05.970
Yeah.

10:06.691 --> 10:10.876
And what you draw around in the book is that Jesus, he really knows us.

10:11.537 --> 10:14.381
And I think that's something in our evangelism.

10:14.421 --> 10:21.170
We perhaps need to be clearer on that it isn't that there's just this authority that

10:21.410 --> 10:26.277
Of course, Jesus is powerful supreme, but he knows us intimately.

10:26.657 --> 10:27.378
He cares.

10:27.438 --> 10:30.362
And that's displayed in the conversation he has with that.

10:30.382 --> 10:31.484
Exactly.

10:31.524 --> 10:41.097
When we talk to our friends and our neighbors, we actually know things about them that they don't know about themselves, or they may not accept.

10:41.257 --> 10:44.561
For example, that God has said eternity in their hearts.

10:45.022 --> 10:47.245
Or they may say, but I believe when you're dead, you're dead.

10:47.605 --> 10:49.628
But we know that that's not true.

10:49.688 --> 10:51.090
Yes.

10:51.426 --> 10:53.829
Yeah, it's a wonderful thing.

10:54.630 --> 10:55.591
I mean, you get it.

10:55.611 --> 11:01.058
It's not in our purview at the moment, but the little guy goes up the tree.

11:01.218 --> 11:02.079
Yeah.

11:02.880 --> 11:06.164
Because he's in a similar situation that people don't really like him.

11:06.244 --> 11:07.145
He's got that itch.

11:07.165 --> 11:07.405
Yeah.

11:07.445 --> 11:07.846
Yeah.

11:07.946 --> 11:08.346
Yeah.

11:08.687 --> 11:13.212
But and who stops under the exact tree and who calls him by name?

11:13.593 --> 11:14.674
How could he call him by name?

11:14.774 --> 11:16.596
And he has come down because he knows.

11:17.597 --> 11:21.362
And it's an amazing thing that the Bible is

11:21.634 --> 11:28.142
isn't that a book that we learn to know as much as it is a book that shows us how much it knows about us?

11:28.242 --> 11:29.244
Yes, yeah.

11:30.525 --> 11:33.469
I think that's what is interesting at these three stories.

11:33.749 --> 11:41.539
They all reveal ourselves, our own situation, but also reveal Christ in that situation.

11:41.639 --> 11:46.085
So the woman at the well, he knew her and he knows us.

11:46.185 --> 11:50.290
And then obviously the paralyzed man, the man lowered through the roof

11:51.394 --> 11:53.978
you draw out that Jesus knew his greatest need.

11:54.178 --> 11:54.639
Right.

11:54.659 --> 12:03.073
Talkers then through this final one of the thief on the cross because of course that illustration and that crunch line of he said I could come.

12:03.794 --> 12:10.885
Talkers through how you kind of studied that story and drew out that lesson.

12:11.887 --> 12:19.058
Well, like everybody else, I've always been fascinated by the fact that here in the extremity of life,

12:19.234 --> 12:31.890
on the knife edge of death, the sense of antagonism and just hatred can come out.

12:31.990 --> 12:38.158
It's not that the closer people get to death, or we should back off, try to be nice, we're going at 15 minutes left.

12:38.779 --> 12:40.381
No, they're both at the same game.

12:40.822 --> 12:42.243
That's the thing that's striking.

12:42.944 --> 12:45.788
And then, this is the great question, isn't it?

12:46.108 --> 12:47.410
How come the one guy

12:47.522 --> 12:48.864
says what he says.

12:49.584 --> 12:56.292
Well, the fight to the matter is that it's a work of grace and that they both were in proximity to Jesus.

12:57.073 --> 12:59.616
They both had heard his cries from the cross.

13:00.517 --> 13:04.862
They both were just violent in their reaction.

13:05.203 --> 13:12.351
And then all of a sudden, you know, I heard the voice of Jesus say, you know, it's that.

13:12.571 --> 13:14.994
And the fact that this man

13:15.426 --> 13:18.150
First of all, he doesn't speak directly to Jesus.

13:18.210 --> 13:19.412
First of all, he speaks to his friend.

13:19.432 --> 13:20.193
He does the thing.

13:20.514 --> 13:24.620
He says, hey, we're up here.

13:24.660 --> 13:27.024
We're supposed to be up here.

13:27.044 --> 13:28.005
We're getting what we deserve.

13:28.466 --> 13:30.229
But this man has done nothing wrong.

13:31.891 --> 13:36.939
Then he says, Lord, would you remember me when you come into your kingdom?

13:38.141 --> 13:40.564
What an amazing request.

13:41.526 --> 13:44.370
And coming out of such a turnaround,

13:44.834 --> 13:48.278
It's like Damascus Road moment, but not on the Damascus Road.

13:48.358 --> 13:51.021
It's the light shines into the darkness.

13:51.642 --> 13:56.487
We're brought out of darkness into this marvelous light by the light that shines upon us.

13:57.208 --> 14:01.613
And then the response of Jesus, yeah, today He will be with me.

14:02.354 --> 14:05.177
Now, the rest of it is conjecture.

14:05.197 --> 14:09.662
I mean, that's the thing that distresses me about this.

14:10.022 --> 14:13.266
Now we go into a flight of fancy.

14:13.474 --> 14:23.688
But I think the salvation in it is, if I can use our phraseology, the salvation in it is, is that Jesus said, yeah, today, you will be with me in paradise.

14:23.748 --> 14:25.711
So the only answer I've got is that.

14:26.392 --> 14:42.834
If you'll bear with me to pick up on the, on the, on the fantasy side of it, I guess, of the story, you in the clip draw out, you know, hey, let's go through the doctrine of justification or what's your view of church, these sorts of things.

14:43.266 --> 14:54.497
Was that a conscious thought you were having at that moment because you see that as a real danger in the church today or a danger outside of the church day?

14:56.239 --> 15:11.474
As you asked the question, I think it might have been almost subliminal in light of what I said earlier, that here we are in a very structured environment where people are dressed in a certain way and they're very orthodox in their position concerning things and perhaps rather

15:11.874 --> 15:16.521
less than kind to people who might not be able to line up accordingly.

15:16.541 --> 15:21.909
I mean, like the average interview for church membership, you know, so did you have you?

15:21.989 --> 15:22.590
Where are you?

15:22.610 --> 15:24.193
You know, how are you doing best than that?

15:24.553 --> 15:26.877
And you coach for church memberships and I didn't do that.

15:26.897 --> 15:28.459
And I haven't been praying very much now.

15:28.479 --> 15:28.980
I know.

15:29.541 --> 15:32.586
And they say, well, you know, what we just put you on hold to the time of year.

15:33.307 --> 15:38.194
But if the entry point in heaven poses those same questions,

15:38.626 --> 15:49.438
And you have only one leg to stand on, one ground on which to take your stand, then it is in Christ alone, you know what I mean?

15:49.458 --> 15:49.938
That's it.

15:50.519 --> 15:54.383
And that's what that man had to say, because that was all he had to say.

15:54.403 --> 16:05.415
He had nothing else going for him, save that he had asked Christ essentially to save him.

16:05.435 --> 16:08.018
And Jesus said, absolutely.

16:08.386 --> 16:11.391
and immediately and irrevocably.

16:11.511 --> 16:13.754
I mean, it's truly amazing.

16:13.774 --> 16:27.135
But the idea of the angel and everything and the supervising angel, part of that is because, you know, I went forward about a 16-year-old at a Billy Graham crusade.

16:27.175 --> 16:29.098
I think I've told you about that.

16:29.318 --> 16:32.443
And the person started to explain to me about how you become Christian.

16:32.463 --> 16:33.345
I said, no, no, no.

16:33.365 --> 16:34.226
I got that part.

16:34.562 --> 16:37.946
And the guy didn't know what to do, because he was reading off a sheet.

16:37.966 --> 16:40.108
So he went away and got the supervisor.

16:40.128 --> 16:41.490
And the supervisor came back.

16:41.810 --> 16:42.951
He tried to work me through.

16:43.512 --> 16:44.132
I said, you know what?

16:44.152 --> 16:45.694
I'm just going to go home and talk to my dad.

16:45.714 --> 16:46.875
I think it is no good.

16:47.216 --> 16:50.259
So part of that, I sent my mind from the get a poor guy at the game.

16:50.279 --> 16:53.302
The guy at Billy Graham, he's now been promoted to glory.

16:53.463 --> 16:57.327
He's got a job on that.

16:57.347 --> 17:03.954
Yeah, he's trying to ease the passage or prevent a wrong kind of belief.

17:04.386 --> 17:10.135
Do you think we're causing a problem that we're making it too difficult for people to come to Christ?

17:11.618 --> 17:15.164
Because doctrine is important, understanding those things.

17:15.685 --> 17:20.192
The Christian life and the response, the action, they're all important.

17:23.838 --> 17:25.581
Well, let's do it from church history.

17:25.761 --> 17:26.322
Let's take

17:26.626 --> 17:30.170
the poor soul that was preaching on the day that Spurgeon was converted.

17:30.731 --> 17:32.012
I mean, he didn't have a sermon.

17:32.052 --> 17:36.578
He didn't have anything going for him except he was the serpent in the wilderness.

17:36.838 --> 17:39.381
Look, you can say, look.

17:39.401 --> 17:41.323
And when he ran out of material, he just said it more.

17:41.723 --> 17:47.170
And then he says to Spurgeon, young man, you, do you look?

17:47.690 --> 17:50.834
And Spurgeon gets out and he walks up the road and he goes, I look.

17:50.978 --> 17:51.699
I looked.

17:52.440 --> 17:56.385
I looked to Jesus and I found in him my light, my son, you know.

17:56.445 --> 18:05.858
And same thing, whatever analogy we want to use, the wedding analogy I use often, you know, I said to people just didn't fight in the last few days.

18:06.499 --> 18:08.502
Any of you got your marriage certificate here with you?

18:09.503 --> 18:09.883
Nobody.

18:10.464 --> 18:11.546
So how do you know you're married?

18:12.928 --> 18:13.849
How do you feel about it?

18:13.969 --> 18:14.950
Are you feeling really strong?

18:14.970 --> 18:16.072
Are you feeling not so strong?

18:17.253 --> 18:18.615
Well, how did it go?

18:18.956 --> 18:20.658
Well, I said I do.

18:20.994 --> 18:21.755
I said, I do.

18:22.356 --> 18:25.662
So you stand before the father alongside Jesus.

18:26.383 --> 18:30.529
The father says to Jesus, son, will you have this sinner?

18:31.471 --> 18:32.973
Jesus says, yes, I died for her.

18:33.715 --> 18:37.160
And then he says to you and you, will you have this Jesus?

18:37.821 --> 18:38.683
No, I ask you how you feel.

18:39.584 --> 18:40.546
It's relational.

18:41.147 --> 18:42.228
But it's not in a vacuum.

18:43.090 --> 18:45.714
Actually, many, many people come to faith in Christ.

18:45.922 --> 18:57.294
On the strength of very, very little background information, save that they know their need and they have discovered that Jesus is the one who meets their need.

18:57.595 --> 19:05.503
And when we say need, we're not talking about the need for a promotion or need for better sanity, but a deep-seated need.

19:05.643 --> 19:06.144
A rescue.

19:06.464 --> 19:07.025
A rescue.

19:07.385 --> 19:12.330
Alienation from God who can bridge this gap.

19:13.151 --> 19:15.794
Jesus.

19:15.938 --> 19:17.140
It's always then through the book.

19:17.160 --> 19:29.076
It's a short book, but it's going through these three stories in which you retell the stories, but then you draw out the application of the gospel from each one so that Jesus knew the woman.

19:30.357 --> 19:35.644
He knew the man's greatest need, the paralyzed man, and he invites us to come.

19:36.325 --> 19:38.208
What's your hope with a book like this?

19:38.969 --> 19:45.938
Well, first, it will have wide circulation so that as many people as possible can

19:46.306 --> 19:51.554
be exposed to the very simplicity of it, and hopefully the clarity of it.

19:51.935 --> 19:58.345
I mean, each of these encounters are not hard to fathom.

19:59.026 --> 20:10.864
And when we open up our hearts towards taking place there, and God may choose just to shine the light there as well, and say, you know, I don't think I'm the thief.

20:11.385 --> 20:12.527
I'm not the woman.

20:12.607 --> 20:14.610
I'm not the thing, but I do know.

20:14.978 --> 20:19.265
that up until last Friday, I thought my biggest need was X.

